1. Architecture: SE-ResNet-18 (Squeeze-and-Excitation ResNet-18) trained from scratch on 20 ImageNet classes.
The network first layer is a 7x7 convolution followed by four residual stages with channel counts 
64-128-256-512, each block enhanced with a Squeeze-and-Excitation attention module that learns per-channel
importance weights. Global average pooling feeds into a single fully-connected layer outputting 20 class logits.
Total parameters: ~11.3M.

Data split: Stratified 3-way split using a fixed seed (42) to guarantee reproducibility.
Final training run uses 90% of the data (80% train + 10% val merged), 
with the held-out 10% test set evaluated once just at the very end.

Optimizer: Adam (lr=1e-3, weight_decay=1e-4) with CosineAnnealingLR decaying smoothly to 0 over 30 epochs.
Loss: CrossEntropyLoss.

2.For all stages of the experiment, 10% of the data was set aside for the final test set.
This left the remaining 90% available for training and validation.
A critical step in this process was converting the raw integer pixel values, which range from 0 to 255,
into 32-bit floating-point numbers between 0.0 and 1.0. This conversion is necessary because neural networks
rely on mathematical operations and gradient descent to update weights. 
The preprocessing phase also included standardizing the image size to 224 by 224, using padding or cropping,
and centering the images uniformly.
 In Stage A, the data was divided into a 30% training set and a 60% validation set.
The strategy was to incrementally expose the model to unseen data to prevent overfitting.
The baseline model drew inspiration from previously built networks and the AlexNet architecture. 
Training this baseline model yielded a best validation accuracy of 0.6952 over a total time of 145.3 minutes.
Since this relatively simple network achieved decent accuracy with few examples,
the decision was made to adjust the split to 50% training and 40% validation for the next stage,
while developing a deeper model architecture.
In Stage B, the data split was adjusted to 50% for training and 40% for validation.
The model architecture was significantly expanded to include six convolutional blocks,
integrating Squeeze-and-Excitation layers and dropout with a probability of 0.5 at each step.
The results was lower accuracy than before.
Then we did the final architecture mentioned above, An alternative ResNet-style architecture.
Tensors, and Augmentation Strategy:
During training, a comprehensive augmentation strategy was applied directly to the training pipeline on the fly.
This meant the model never saw the exact same version of an image twice,
forcing it to learn invariance to visual changes rather than memorizing specific details.
The augmentations were designed to introduce a wide variety of image distortions.
Random resized crops with prior padding helped the model recognize objects at different scales
and positions without relying on perfectly centered objects. Additional transformations involved:
random horizontal and vertical flips, 30-degree rotations, and color jittering to alter brightness, 
contrast, saturation, and hue. The pipeline also incorporated random grayscale conversion, perspective distortion, 
Gaussian blur, sharpness adjustments, and random erasing to simulate partial occlusion. 
To further enhance the model's robustness, we extracted an additional 200 images per class from the
Hugging Face library and integrated them directly into our training set. 
The model was then thoroughly evaluated on the final test set, 
and these resulting weights are the ones we ultimately submitted.

